  grammarRules: [
    {
      id: 'g1',
      title: 'SOV Word Order',
      body: 'Navajo is Subject-Object-Verb. "The man eats the bread" → "The man bread eats." The verb always comes at the end of the sentence. This is strictly maintained, unlike English which can shift word order for emphasis.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g2',
      title: 'Four Tones',
      body: 'Navajo has four lexical tones: high (marked ´), low (unmarked), rising, and falling. A change in tone completely changes the meaning of a word. This is one reason Navajo was such an effective military code  -  even native speakers of related languages couldn\'t decode it easily.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g3',
      title: 'Inalienable Possession (Body Parts & Family)',
      body: 'Body parts and family terms cannot stand alone in Navajo  -  they must always have a possessive prefix. "Shimá" = "my mother"; "nimá" = "your mother"; "amá" = "someone\'s mother" (general). You cannot say just "má" (mother) without specifying whose mother. This is called inalienable possession.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g4',
      title: 'Verb Complexity',
      body: 'A single Navajo verb can encode the subject, object, tense, aspect, mode, direction, and the physical shape of the object. The English verb "give" is expressed by eleven different Navajo verbs depending on what is being given. Verbs are built by stacking prefixes before a root.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g5',
      title: 'No "To Be" (Copula) for Some Constructions',
      body: 'Colors in Navajo are verbs, not adjectives. "łizhin" doesn\'t mean "black"  -  it means "it is black." Similarly, many states are expressed verbally. The word "Nizhóní" = "It is beautiful / beautiful" acts as a verb.'
    },
    {
      id: 'g6',
      title: 'Animacy Hierarchy',
      body: 'Navajo ranks beings on an animacy hierarchy. Humans > animals > plants > objects. The more animate being must function as subject first  -  this affects which verb form is chosen. This is why Navajo sentences can sometimes seem backwards compared to English.'
    }
  ],

